        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Montreal</placeName>
                <date>9<hi rend="sup">th</hi> June 5617</date>.</p>
            <p>
                <addressee>Rev. Isaac Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">Dear Sir</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">The <date>June</date> Occident first<lb/> received informs me of
                your having entered<lb/> once more into the active duties of the<lb/> ministry, and
                although you may be said<lb/> to have never wholly relinquished them, yet<lb/> I
                warmly congratulate you on your<lb/> becoming Hazan of the Synagogue Beth El
                Emeth<lb/> Minhag sephardim to which with all my<lb/> heart I wish the fullest
                possible amount<lb/> of success and prosperity. You may think<lb/> me tardy in
                expressing these wishes, but<lb/> recollect, dear sir, the first notification<lb/> I
                had from you of the event, was your<lb/> article in the <date>June</date> Occident.
                True, <persName>Miss<lb/> Sarah Joseph</persName> mentioned to me in your<lb/> name
                that the Synagogue would probably be<lb/> opened for <add>שבועות</add>; at which I
                of course<lb/> expressed my gratification. And believe me<lb/> that for your sake I
                was much pleased<lb/> to hear of the movement. As to the absurd</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>objection that there is no room<lb/> for two Portuguese synagogues—this is<lb/> more
                astonishing than annoying. When<lb/>
                <sic>hundred</sic> of German &amp; Polish Congregations<lb/> are formed under the
                most unpromising<lb/> auspices, why in the name of reason should<lb/> we not
                multiply—or attempt to multiply<lb/> congregations having so superior a ritual<lb/>
                as the Portuguese. I sincerely believe the<lb/> greatest blow to wild reform
                among<lb/> the German &amp; Polish Kehilloth is the<lb/> introduction of the minhag
                sephardim<lb/> among congregations who cannot <add>?</add><lb/> long troublesome
                Peyutim Keroboth &amp;c<lb/> I will not trouble you however with<lb/> a long
                disquisition on a theme you have<lb/> yourself often pronounced on.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">You have no doubt heard of<lb/> the death of a very valued old
                friend<lb/> of mine—and correspondent of the Occident<lb/>
                <persName>Mr. J. Peynado</persName> of <placeName>Hackney, England</placeName>,<lb/>
                As my father writes me—He was one<lb/> of the last <hi rend="underline">real</hi>
                (Portuguese) <hi rend="underline">gentlemen</hi><lb/> for which K. K. <add>?</add>
                <placeName>London</placeName></p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>was celebrated. The material of the <add>קהל</add> is<lb/> yet not had, but new like
                    <persName>Jo Peynardo</persName><lb/> one does not meet with every day. To
                know<lb/> him was to love him. Truly religious (altho,<lb/> having as you know
                peculiar views of some<lb/> matters) he was strictly honorable, urbane<lb/> and
                charitable. His zeal for his religion often<lb/> as you well know, led him to take
                up the<lb/> pen, and he even administered a pretty<lb/> severe castigation to
                    <persName>Dr McCaul</persName> in defense of<lb/>
                <persName>Miss Aguilar</persName>. I have no doubt you have<lb/> some materials for
                an obituary notice of<lb/> him in the Occident. He deserves one <add>עליו
                    השלום</add></p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I perceive <persName>Jacobs</persName> of
                    <placeName>Charleston</placeName><lb/> has resigned. The Israelite who wanted
                to<lb/> say something bitter and could not <add>ויקבוץ וגו</add><lb/> says it is one
                disease of the system of<lb/> the orthodoxy. Do you know any other<lb/> reason for I
                expect there must be another.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">When do you commence the “Advocate?<lb/>
                <persName>Mrs DeSola</persName> desires me to congratulate<lb/> you in her name on
                your resumption<lb/> of clerical duties, and she wishes you<lb/> as do I, many years
                of happiness<lb/> in their discharge. I shall be very</p>
            <pb n="4"/>
            <p>glad to hear from you when you<lb/> have leisure, and believe me as ever</p>
            <p rend="indent(7)">Yours faithfully</p>
            <p rend="indent(7)">
                <persName role="author">Abraham de Sola</persName>
            </p>
        </body>
